# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: markov-chain-monte-carlo
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] In statistics, **Gibbs sampling** or a **Gibbs sampler** is a Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) algorithm for sampling from a specified multivariate probability distribution when direct sampling from the joint distribution is difficult, but sampling from the conditional distribution is more practical.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Typically, some of the variables correspond to observations whose values are known, and hence do not need to be sampled.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Gibbs sampling is commonly used as a means of statistical inference, especially Bayesian inference.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] It is a randomized algorithm (i.e. an algorithm that makes use of random numbers), and is an alternative to deterministic algorithms for statistical inference such as the expectation–maximization algorithm (EM).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] As with other MCMC algorithms, Gibbs sampling generates a Markov chain of samples, each of which is correlated with nearby samples.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] As a result, care must be taken if independent samples are desired.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Samples from the beginning of the chain (the *burn-in period*) may not accurately represent the desired distribution and are usually discarded.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Gibbs sampling is named after the physicist Josiah Willard Gibbs, in reference to an analogy between the sampling algorithm and statistical physics.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] The algorithm was described by brothers Stuart and Donald Geman in 1984, some eight decades after the death of Gibbs, and became popularized in the statistics community for calculating marginal probability distribution, especially the posterior distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] In its basic version, Gibbs sampling is a special case of the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Gibbs sampling is applicable when the joint distribution is not known explicitly or is difficult to sample from directly, but the conditional distribution of each variable is known and is easy (or at least, easier) to sample from.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] The Gibbs sampling algorithm generates an instance from the distribution of each variable in turn, conditional on the current values of the other variables.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] It can be shown that the sequence of samples constitutes a Markov chain, and the stationary distribution of that Markov chain is just the sought-after joint distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Gibbs sampling is particularly well-adapted to sampling the posterior distribution of a Bayesian network, since Bayesian networks are typically specified as a collection of conditional distributions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Gibbs sampling, in its basic incarnation, is a special case of the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] The point of Gibbs sampling is that given a multivariate distribution it is simpler to sample from a conditional distribution than to marginalize by integrating over a joint distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Suppose we want to obtain k samples of a n -dimensional random vector $\mathbf {X} =(X_{1},\dots ,X_{n})$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] "Proportional to" in this case means that the denominator is not a function of $x_{j}$ and thus is the same for all values of $x_{j}$ ; it forms part of the normalization constant for the distribution over $x_{j}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] If the distribution is continuous and of a known form, the normalization constant will also be known.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] In other cases, the normalization constant can usually be ignored, as most sampling methods do not require it.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Gibbs sampling is commonly used for statistical inference (e.g. determining the best value of a parameter, such as determining the number of people likely to shop at a particular store on a given day, the candidate a voter will most likely vote for, etc.).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] The idea is that observed data is incorporated into the sampling process by creating separate variables for each piece of observed data and fixing the variables in question to their observed values, rather than sampling from those variables.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] The distribution of the remaining variables is then effectively a posterior distribution conditioned on the observed data.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] The most likely value of a desired parameter (the mode) could then simply be selected by choosing the sample value that occurs most commonly; this is essentially equivalent to maximum a posteriori estimation of a parameter.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] For example, for a unimodal distribution the mean (expected value) is usually similar to the mode (most common value), but if the distribution is skewed in one direction, the mean will be moved in that direction, which effectively accounts for the extra probability mass in that direction.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Although some of the variables typically correspond to parameters of interest, others are uninteresting ("nuisance") variables introduced into the model to properly express the relationships among variables.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Although the sampled values represent the joint distribution over all variables, the nuisance variables can simply be ignored when computing expected values or modes; this is equivalent to marginalizing over the nuisance variables.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] When a value for multiple variables is desired, the expected value is simply computed over each variable separately.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Supervised learning, unsupervised learning and semi-supervised learning (aka learning with missing values) can all be handled by simply fixing the values of all variables whose values are known, and sampling from the remainder.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] For observed data, there will be one variable for each observation—rather than, for example, one variable corresponding to the sample mean or sample variance of a set of observations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] In fact, there generally will be no variables at all corresponding to concepts such as "sample mean" or "sample variance".
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Instead, in such a case there will be variables representing the unknown true mean and true variance, and the determination of sample values for these variables results automatically from the operation of the Gibbs sampler.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Generalized linear models (i.e. variations of linear regression) can sometimes be handled by Gibbs sampling as well.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] For example, probit regression for determining the probability of a given binary (yes/no) choice, with normally distributed priors placed over the regression coefficients, can be implemented with Gibbs sampling because it is possible to add additional variables and take advantage of conjugacy.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] However, logistic regression cannot be handled this way.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] One possibility is to approximate the logistic function with a mixture (typically 7–9) of normal distributions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] More commonly, however, Metropolis–Hastings is used instead of Gibbs sampling.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Suppose that a sample $\left.X\right.$ is taken from a distribution depending on a parameter vector $\theta \in \Theta \,\!$ of length $\left.d\right.$ , with prior distribution $g(\theta _{1},\ldots ,\theta _{d})$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] It may be that $\left.d\right.$ is very large and that numerical integration to find the marginal densities of the $\left.\theta _{i}\right.$ would be computationally expensive.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] These steps define a reversible Markov chain with the desired invariant distribution $\left.g\right.$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Define $x\sim _{j}y$ if $\left.x_{i}=y_{i}\right.$ for all $i\neq j$ and let $\left.p_{xy}\right.$ denote the probability of a jump from $x\in \Theta$ to $y\in \Theta$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] since $x\sim _{j}y$ is an equivalence relation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Thus the detailed balance equations are satisfied, implying the chain is reversible and it has invariant distribution $\left.g\right.$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] In practice, the index $\left.j\right.$ is not chosen at random, and the chain cycles through the indexes in order.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] In general this gives a non-stationary Markov process, but each individual step will still be reversible, and the overall process will still have the desired stationary distribution (as long as the chain can access all states under the fixed ordering).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Let y denote observations generated from the sampling distribution $f(y|\theta )$ and $\pi (\theta )$ be a prior supported on the parameter space $\Theta$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] where the marginal likelihood $m(y)=\int _{\Theta }f(y|\theta )\cdot \pi (\theta )d\theta$ is assumed to be finite for all y .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] where $\times$ represents the Cartesian product.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Each component parameter space $\Theta _{i}$ can be a set of scalar components, subvectors, or matrices.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Define a set $\Theta _{-i}$ that complements the $\Theta _{i}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Note that Gibbs sampler is operated by the iterative Monte Carlo scheme within a cycle.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] The S number of samples $\{\theta ^{(s)}\}_{s=1}^{S}$ drawn by the above algorithm formulates Markov Chains with the invariant distribution to be the target density $\pi (\theta |y)$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] namely, posterior mutual information, posterior differential entropy, and posterior conditional differential entropy, respectively.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] We can similarly define information theoretic quantities $I(\theta _{-i};\theta _{i})$ , $H(\theta _{i})$ , and $H(\theta _{i}|\theta _{-i})$ by interchanging the i and $-i$ in the defined quantities.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] The mutual information $I(\theta _{i};\theta _{-i})$ quantifies the reduction in uncertainty of random quantity $\theta _{i}$ once we know $\theta _{-i}$ , a posteriori.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] It vanishes if and only if $\theta _{i}$ and $\theta _{-i}$ are marginally independent, a posterior.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] The mutual information $I(\theta _{i};\theta _{-i})$ can be interpreted as the quantity that is transmitted from the i -th step to the $i+1$ -th step within a single cycle of the Gibbs sampler.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Numerous variations of the basic Gibbs sampler exist.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] The goal of these variations is to reduce the autocorrelation between samples sufficiently to overcome any added computational costs.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] In hierarchical Bayesian models with categorical variables, such as latent Dirichlet allocation and various other models used in natural language processing, it is quite common to collapse out the Dirichlet distributions that are typically used as prior distributions over the categorical variables.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] The result of this collapsing introduces dependencies among all the categorical variables dependent on a given Dirichlet prior, and the joint distribution of these variables after collapsing is a Dirichlet-multinomial distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] The conditional distribution of a given categorical variable in this distribution, conditioned on the others, assumes an extremely simple form that makes Gibbs sampling even easier than if the collapsing had not been done.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Collapsing out a Dirichlet prior introduces dependencies among all the categorical children dependent on that prior — but *no* extra dependencies among any other categorical children.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] (This is important to keep in mind, for example, when there are multiple Dirichlet priors related by the same hyperprior.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Nodes not dependent on the same prior **must not** be counted.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] The same rule applies in other iterative inference methods, such as variational Bayes or expectation maximization; however, if the method involves keeping partial counts, then the partial counts for the value in question must be summed across all the other dependent nodes.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Sometimes this summed up partial count is termed the *expected count* or similar.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] See the article on the Dirichlet-multinomial distribution for a detailed discussion.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] See the article on the Dirichlet-multinomial distribution for more discussion, including in the context of a topic model.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] In general, any conjugate prior can be collapsed out, if its only children have distributions conjugate to it.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] The relevant math is discussed in the article on compound distributions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] If there is only one child node, the result will often assume a known distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] For example, collapsing an inverse-gamma-distributed variance out of a network with a single Gaussian child will yield a Student's t-distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] (For that matter, collapsing both the mean and variance of a single Gaussian child will still yield a Student's t-distribution, provided both are conjugate, i.e.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] If there are multiple child nodes, they will all become dependent, as in the Dirichlet-categorical case.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] The resulting joint distribution will have a closed form that resembles in some ways the compound distribution, although it will have a product of a number of factors, one for each child node, in it.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Furthermore, the posterior predictive distribution has the same density as the basic compound distribution of a single node, although with different parameters.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] The general formula is given in the article on compound distributions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Similarly, the result of compounding out the gamma prior of a number of Poisson-distributed nodes causes the conditional distribution of one node given the others to assume a negative binomial distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] In these cases where compounding produces a well-known distribution, efficient sampling procedures often exist, and using them will often (although not necessarily) be more efficient than not collapsing, and instead sampling both prior and child nodes separately.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] In the case where the child nodes of the collapsed nodes themselves have children, the conditional distribution of one of these child nodes given all other nodes in the graph will have to take into account the distribution of these second-level children.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] In particular, the resulting conditional distribution will be proportional to a product of the compound distribution as defined above, and the conditional distributions of all of the child nodes given their parents (but not given their own children).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] This follows from the fact that the full conditional distribution is proportional to the joint distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] If the child nodes of the collapsed nodes are continuous, this distribution will generally not be of a known form, and may well be difficult to sample from despite the fact that a closed form can be written, for the same reasons as described above for non-well-known compound distributions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] However, in the particular case that the child nodes are discrete, sampling is feasible, regardless of whether the children of these child nodes are continuous or discrete.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] In fact, the principle involved here is described in fair detail in the article on the Dirichlet-multinomial distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] It is also possible to extend Gibbs sampling in various ways.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] For example, in the case of variables whose conditional distribution is not easy to sample from, a single iteration of slice sampling or the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm can be used to sample from the variables in question.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] It is also possible to incorporate variables that are not random variables, but whose value is deterministically computed from other variables.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Generalized linear models, e.g. logistic regression (aka "maximum entropy models"), can be incorporated in this fashion.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] There are two ways that Gibbs sampling can fail.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] The first is when there are islands of high-probability states, with no paths between them.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] For example, consider a probability distribution over 2-bit vectors, where the vectors (0,0) and (1,1) each have probability ⁠1/2⁠, but the other two vectors (0,1) and (1,0) have probability zero.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Gibbs sampling will become trapped in one of the two high-probability vectors, and will never reach the other one.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] More generally, for any distribution over high-dimensional, real-valued vectors, if two particular elements of the vector are perfectly correlated (or perfectly anti-correlated), those two elements will become stuck, and Gibbs sampling will never be able to change them.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] The second problem can happen even when all states have nonzero probability and there is only a single island of high-probability states.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] For example, consider a probability distribution over 100-bit vectors, where the all-zeros vector occurs with probability ⁠1/2⁠, and all other vectors are equally probable, and so have a probability of ${\frac {1}{2(2^{100}-1)}}$ each.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] If you want to estimate the probability of the zero vector, it would be sufficient to take 100 or 1000 samples from the true distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] That would very likely give an answer very close to ⁠1/2⁠.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] But you would probably have to take more than $2^{100}$ samples from Gibbs sampling to get the same result.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] No computer could do this in a lifetime.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] This problem occurs no matter how long the burn-in period is.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] This is because in the true distribution, the zero vector occurs half the time, and those occurrences are randomly mixed in with the nonzero vectors.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Even a small sample will see both zero and nonzero vectors.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] But Gibbs sampling will alternate between returning only the zero vector for long periods (about $2^{99}$ in a row), then only nonzero vectors for long periods (about $2^{99}$ in a row).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] Thus convergence to the true distribution is extremely slow, requiring much more than $2^{99}$ steps; taking this many steps is not computationally feasible in a reasonable time period.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] The slow convergence here can be seen as a consequence of the curse of dimensionality.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] A problem like this can be solved by block sampling the entire 100-bit vector at once.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/gibbs-sampling] (This assumes that the 100-bit vector is part of a larger set of variables.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] The **Hamiltonian Monte Carlo** algorithm (originally known as **hybrid Monte Carlo**) is a Markov chain Monte Carlo method for obtaining a sequence of random samples whose distribution converges to a target probability distribution that is difficult to sample directly.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] This sequence can be used to estimate integrals of the target distribution, such as expected values and moments.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Hamiltonian Monte Carlo corresponds to an instance of the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm, with a Hamiltonian dynamics evolution simulated using a time-reversible and volume-preserving numerical integrator (typically the leapfrog integrator) to propose a move to a new point in the state space.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] The reduced correlation means fewer Markov chain samples are needed to approximate integrals with respect to the target probability distribution for a given Monte Carlo error.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] The algorithm was originally proposed by Simon Duane, Anthony Kennedy, Brian Pendleton and Duncan Roweth in 1987 for calculations in lattice quantum chromodynamics.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Neal showed how the method could be used for a broader class of statistical problems, in particular artificial neural networks.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] But the burden of having to provide the algorithm with gradients of the model graph delayed its wider adoption in statistics and other quantitative disciplines, until in the mid-2010s the developers of Stan implemented HMC in combination with automatic differentiation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Suppose the target distribution to sample is $f(\mathbf {x} )$ for $\mathbf {x} \in \mathbb {R} ^{d}$ ( $d\geq 1$ ) and a chain of samples $\mathbf {X} _{0},\mathbf {X} _{1},\mathbf {X} _{2},\ldots$ is required.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] where $x_{i}$ and $p_{i}$ are the i th component of the position and momentum vector respectively and H is the Hamiltonian.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] where $U(\mathbf {x} )$ is the potential energy.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] which comes from the Boltzmann's factor.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Note that the Hamiltonian H is dimensionless in this formulation because the exponential probability weight $\exp \left(-H\right)$ has to be well defined.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] For example, in simulations at finite temperature T the factor $k_{\text{B}}T$ (with the Boltzmann constant $k_{\text{B}}$ ) is directly absorbed into U and M .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] The algorithm requires a positive integer for number of leapfrog steps L and a positive number for the step size $\Delta t$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Suppose the chain is at $\mathbf {X} _{n}=\mathbf {x} _{n}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] First, a random Gaussian momentum $\mathbf {p} _{n}(0)$ is drawn from ${\text{N}}\left(\mathbf {0} ,M\right)$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Next, the particle will run under Hamiltonian dynamics for time $L\Delta t$ , this is done by solving the Hamilton's equations numerically using the leapfrog algorithm.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] These equations are to be applied to $\mathbf {x} _{n}(0)$ and $\mathbf {p} _{n}(0)$ L times to obtain $\mathbf {x} _{n}(L\Delta t)$ and $\mathbf {p} _{n}(L\Delta t)$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] The leapfrog algorithm is an approximate solution to the motion of non-interacting classical particles.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] If exact, the solution will never change the initial randomly-generated energy distribution, as energy is conserved for each particle in the presence of a classical potential energy field.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] In order to reach a thermodynamic equilibrium distribution, particles must have some sort of interaction with, for example, a surrounding heat bath, so that the entire system can take on different energies with probabilities according to the Boltzmann distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] One way to move the system towards a thermodynamic equilibrium distribution is to change the state of the particles using the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] So first, one applies the leapfrog step, then a Metropolis-Hastings step.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] A full update consists of first randomly sampling the momenta $\mathbf {p}$ (independently of the previous iterations), then integrating the equations of motion (e.g. with leapfrog), and finally obtaining the new configuration from the Metropolis-Hastings accept/reject step.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] This updating mechanism is repeated to obtain $\mathbf {X} _{n+1},\mathbf {X} _{n+2},\mathbf {X} _{n+3},\ldots$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] The No U-Turn Sampler (NUTS) is an extension by controlling the number of steps L automatically.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] For example, in the one dimensional ${\text{N}}(0,1/{\sqrt {k}})$ case, the potential is $U(x)=kx^{2}/2$ which corresponds to the potential of a simple harmonic oscillator.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] For L too large, the particle will oscillate and thus waste computational time.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] For L too small, the particle will behave like a random walk.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Loosely, NUTS runs the Hamiltonian dynamics both forwards and backwards in time randomly until a U-Turn condition is satisfied.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] When that happens, a random point from the path is chosen for the MCMC sample and the process is repeated from that new point.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] In detail, a binary tree is constructed to trace the path of the leap frog steps.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] To produce a MCMC sample, an iterative procedure is conducted.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Let $\mathbf {x} _{n}^{+}$ and $\mathbf {p} _{n}^{+}$ be the position and momentum of the forward particle respectively.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] In each iteration, the binary tree selects at random uniformly to move the forward particle forwards in time or the backward particle backwards in time.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] Also for each iteration, the number of leap frog steps increase by a factor of 2.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] For example, in the first iteration, the forward particle moves forwards in time using 1 leap frog step.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] In the next iteration, the backward particle moves backwards in time using 2 leap frog steps.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/hamiltonian-monte-carlo] This is usually satisfied if the remaining HMC parameters are sensible.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] In statistics, **kernel density estimation** (**KDE**) is the application of kernel smoothing for probability density estimation, i.e., a non-parametric method to estimate the probability density function of a random variable based on *kernels* as weights.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] KDE answers a fundamental data smoothing problem where inferences about the population are made based on a finite data sample.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] In some fields such as signal processing and econometrics it is also termed the **Parzen–Rosenblatt window** method, after Emanuel Parzen and Murray Rosenblatt, who are usually credited with independently creating it in its current form.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] One of the famous applications of kernel density estimation is in estimating the class-conditional marginal densities of data when using a naive Bayes classifier, which can improve its prediction accuracy.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] Let $\mathbf {x} =\left(x_{1},x_{2},x_{3},...\right)$ be independent and identically distributed samples drawn from some univariate distribution with an unknown density *f* at any given point x.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] We are interested in estimating the shape of this function *f*.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] A kernel with subscript h is called the *scaled kernel* and defined as *K**h*(*x*) = ⁠1/*h*⁠ *K*(⁠*x*/*h*⁠).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] Intuitively one wants to choose h as small as the data will allow; however, there is always a trade-off between the bias of the estimator and its variance.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] The choice of bandwidth is discussed in more detail below.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] A range of kernel functions are commonly used: uniform, triangular, biweight, triweight, Epanechnikov (parabolic), normal, and others.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] The Epanechnikov kernel is optimal in a mean square error sense, though the loss of efficiency is small for the kernels listed previously.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] Due to its convenient mathematical properties, the normal kernel is often used, which means *K*(*x*) = *ϕ*(*x*), where ϕ is the standard normal density function.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] The construction of a kernel density estimate finds interpretations in fields outside of density estimation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] For example, in thermodynamics, this is equivalent to the amount of heat generated when heat kernels (the fundamental solution to the heat equation) are placed at each data point locations *xi*.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] Similar methods are used to construct discrete Laplace operators on point clouds for manifold learning (e.g. diffusion map).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] Kernel density estimates are closely related to histograms, but can be endowed with properties such as smoothness or continuity by using a suitable kernel.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] For the histogram, first, the horizontal axis is divided into sub-intervals or bins which cover the range of the data: In this case, six bins each of width 2.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] Whenever a data point falls inside this interval, a box of height 1/12 is placed there.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] If more than one data point falls inside the same bin, the boxes are stacked on top of each other.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] For the kernel density estimate, normal kernels with a standard deviation of 1.5 (indicated by the red dashed lines) are placed on each of the data points *xi*.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] The kernels are summed to make the kernel density estimate (solid blue curve).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] The smoothness of the kernel density estimate (compared to the discreteness of the histogram) illustrates how kernel density estimates converge faster to the true underlying density for continuous random variables.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] The bandwidth of the kernel is a free parameter which exhibits a strong influence on the resulting estimate.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] To illustrate its effect, we take a simulated random sample from the standard normal distribution (plotted at the blue spikes in the rug plot on the horizontal axis).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] The grey curve is the true density (a normal density with mean 0 and variance 1).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] In comparison, the red curve is *undersmoothed* since it contains too many spurious data artifacts arising from using a bandwidth *h* = 0.05, which is too small.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] The green curve is *oversmoothed* since using the bandwidth *h* = 2 obscures much of the underlying structure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] The black curve with a bandwidth of *h* = 0.337 is considered to be optimally smoothed since its density estimate is close to the true density.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] An extreme situation is encountered in the limit $h\to 0$ (no smoothing), where the estimate is a sum of n delta functions centered at the coordinates of analyzed samples.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] In the other extreme limit $h\to \infty$ the estimate retains the shape of the used kernel, centered on the mean of the samples (completely smooth).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] where *o* is the little o notation, and n the sample size (as above).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] where ${\textstyle R(g)=\int g(x)^{2}\,dx}$ for a function *g*, ${\textstyle m_{2}(K)=\int x^{2}K(x)\,dx}$ and $f''$ is the second derivative of f and K is the kernel.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] Neither the AMISE nor the *h*AMISE formulas can be used directly since they involve the unknown density function f or its second derivative $f''$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] To overcome that difficulty, a variety of automatic, data-based methods have been developed to select the bandwidth.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] Several review studies have been undertaken to compare their efficacies, with the general consensus that the plug-in selectors and cross validation selectors are the most useful over a wide range of data sets.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] Substituting any bandwidth h which has the same asymptotic order *n*−1/5 as *h*AMISE into the AMISE gives that AMISE(*h*) = *O*(*n*−4/5), where *O* is the big *O* notation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] It can be shown that, under weak assumptions, there cannot exist a non-parametric estimator that converges at a faster rate than the kernel estimator.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] Note that the *n*−4/5 rate is slower than the typical *n*−1 convergence rate of parametric methods.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] If the bandwidth is not held fixed, but is varied depending upon the location of either the estimate (balloon estimator) or the samples (pointwise estimator), this produces a particularly powerful method termed adaptive or variable bandwidth kernel density estimation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] Bandwidth selection for kernel density estimation of heavy-tailed distributions is relatively difficult.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] An h value is considered more robust when it improves the fit for long-tailed and skewed distributions or for bimodal mixture distributions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] Another modification that will improve the model is to reduce the factor from 1.06 to 0.9.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] This approximation is termed the *normal distribution approximation*, Gaussian approximation, or *Silverman's rule of thumb*.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] While this rule of thumb is easy to compute, it should be used with caution as it can yield widely inaccurate estimates when the density is not close to being normal.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] The estimate based on the rule-of-thumb bandwidth is significantly oversmoothed.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] One difficulty with applying this inversion formula is that it leads to a diverging integral, since the estimate ${\hat {\varphi }}(t)$ is unreliable for large t's.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] To circumvent this problem, the estimator ${\hat {\varphi }}(t)$ is multiplied by a damping function *ψh*(*t*) = *ψ*(*ht*), which is equal to 1 at the origin and then falls to 0 at infinity.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] The "bandwidth parameter" h controls how fast we try to dampen the function ${\hat {\varphi }}(t)$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] In particular when h is small, then *ψh*(*t*) will be approximately one for a large range of t's, which means that ${\hat {\varphi }}(t)$ remains practically unaltered in the most important region of t's.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] The most common choice for function *ψ* is either the uniform function *ψ*(*t*) = **1**{−1 ≤ *t* ≤ 1}, which effectively means truncating the interval of integration in the inversion formula to [−1/*h*, 1/*h*], or the Gaussian function *ψ*(*t*) = *e**−πt*2.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] where *K* is the Fourier transform of the damping function *ψ*.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] Thus the kernel density estimator coincides with the characteristic function density estimator.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] Namely, M is the collection of points for which the density function is locally maximized.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] A natural estimator of M is a plug-in from KDE, where $g(x)$ and $\lambda _{1}(x)$ are KDE version of $g(x)$ and $\lambda _{1}(x)$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] Under mild assumptions, $M_{c}$ is a consistent estimator of M .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/kernel-density-estimation] Note that one can use the mean shift algorithm to compute the estimator $M_{c}$ numerically.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In statistics, **Markov chain Monte Carlo** (**MCMC**) is a class of algorithms used to draw samples from a probability distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Given a probability distribution, one can construct a Markov chain whose elements' distribution approximates it, i.e. the Markov chain's equilibrium distribution matches the target distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The more steps that are included, the more closely the distribution of the sample matches the actual desired distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Markov chain Monte Carlo methods are used to study probability distributions that are too complex or too high dimensional to study with analytic techniques alone.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Various algorithms exist for constructing such Markov chains, including the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Markov chain Monte Carlo methods create samples from a continuous random variable, with probability density proportional to a known function.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These samples can be used to evaluate an integral over that variable, as its expected value or variance.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Practically, an ensemble of chains is generally developed, starting from a set of points arbitrarily chosen and sufficiently distant from each other.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These chains are stochastic processes of "walkers" which move around randomly according to an algorithm that looks for places with a reasonably high contribution to the integral to move into next, assigning them higher probabilities.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Random walk Monte Carlo methods are a kind of random simulation or Monte Carlo method.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] However, whereas the random samples of the integrand used in a conventional Monte Carlo integration are statistically independent, those used in MCMC are autocorrelated.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Correlations of samples introduces the need to use the Markov chain central limit theorem when estimating the error of mean values.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These algorithms create Markov chains such that they have an equilibrium distribution which is proportional to the function given.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The development of MCMC methods is deeply rooted in the early exploration of Monte Carlo (MC) techniques in the mid-20th century, particularly in physics.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These developments were marked by the Metropolis algorithm proposed by Nicholas Metropolis, Arianna W.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Rosenbluth, Marshall Rosenbluth, Augusta H.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Teller, and Edward Teller in 1953, which was designed to tackle high-dimensional integration problems using early computers.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Hastings generalized this algorithm and inadvertently introduced the component-wise updating idea, later known as Gibbs sampling.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Simultaneously, the theoretical foundations for Gibbs sampling were being developed, such as the Hammersley–Clifford theorem from Julian Besag's 1974 paper.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Although the seeds of MCMC were sown earlier, including the formal naming of Gibbs sampling in image processing by Stuart Geman and Donald Geman (1984) and the data augmentation method by Martin A.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This transformation was accompanied by significant theoretical advancements, such as Luke Tierney's (1994) rigorous treatment of MCMC convergence, and Jun S.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Liu, Wong, and Augustine Kong's (1994, 1995) analysis of Gibbs sampler structure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Subsequent developments further expanded the MCMC toolkit, including particle filters (Sequential Monte Carlo) for sequential problems, Perfect sampling aiming for exact simulation (Jim Propp and David B.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Green, 1995) for handling variable-dimension models, and deeper investigations into convergence diagnostics and the central limit theorem.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Overall, the evolution of MCMC represents a paradigm shift in statistical computation, enabling the analysis of numerous previously intractable complex models and continually expanding the scope and impact of statistics.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Suppose *(Xn)* is a Markov Chain in the general state space ${\mathcal {X}}$ with specific properties.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Particularly, we hope to establish the Law of Large Numbers and the Central Limit Theorem for MCMC.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In the following, we state some definitions and theorems necessary for the important convergence results.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In short, we need the existence of invariant measure and Harris recurrent to establish the Law of Large Numbers of MCMC (Ergodic Theorem).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] And we need aperiodicity, irreducibility and extra conditions such as reversibility to ensure the Central Limit Theorem holds in MCMC.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Recall that in the discrete setting, a Markov chain is said to be *irreducible* if it is possible to reach any state from any other state in a finite number of steps with positive probability.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] However, in the continuous setting, point-to-point transitions have zero probability.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In this case, **φ-irreducibility** generalizes irreducibility by using a reference measure φ on the measurable space $({\mathcal {X}},{\mathcal {B}}({\mathcal {X}}))$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This is a more general definition for irreducibility of a Markov chain in non-discrete state space.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In the discrete case, an irreducible Markov chain is said to be *aperiodic* if it has period 1.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The chain $(X_{n})$ is said to be **Harris recurrent** if there exists a measure $\psi$ such that the chain is $\psi$ -irreducible and every measurable set A with $\psi (A)>0$ is Harris recurrent.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This definition is only needed when the state space ${\mathcal {X}}$ is uncountable.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In the countable case, recurrence corresponds to $\mathbb {E} _{x}[\eta _{x}]=\infty$ , which is equivalent to $P_{x}(\tau _{x}<\infty )=1$ for all $x\in {\mathcal {X}}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When there exists an *invariant probability measure* for a **ψ-irreducible** (hence recurrent) chain, the chain is said to be **positive recurrent**.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Recurrent chains that do not allow for a finite invariant measure are called **null recurrent**.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In applications of Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC), a very useful criterion for Harris recurrence involves the use of bounded harmonic functions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These functions are *invariant* under the transition kernel in the functional sense, and they help characterize Harris recurrence.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This theorem provides a fundamental justification for the use of Markov Chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods, and it serves as the counterpart of the Law of Large Numbers (LLN) in classical Monte Carlo.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] An important aspect of this result is that $\pi$ does not need to be a probability measure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Therefore, there can be some type of strong stability even if the chain is null recurrent.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Moreover, the Markov chain can be started from arbitrary state.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This is the Ergodic Theorem that we are more familiar with.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] There are several conditions under which the Central Limit Theorem (CLT) holds for Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) methods.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] One of the most commonly used is the condition of **reversibility**.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] A stationary Markov chain $(X_{n})$ is said to be **reversible** if the distribution of $X_{n+1}$ given $X_{n+2}=x$ is the same as the distribution of $X_{n+1}$ given $X_{n}=x$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] for every pair $(x,y)$ in the state space.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Even though reversibility is a restrictive assumption in theory, it is often easily satisfied in practical MCMC algorithms by introducing auxiliary variables or using symmetric proposal mechanisms.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] There are many other conditions that can be used to establish CLT for MCMC such as geometric ergodicity and the discrete state space.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] MCMC methods produce autocorrelated samples, in contrast to standard Monte Carlo techniques that draw independent samples.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Autocorrelation means successive draws from the Markov chain are statistically dependent, so each new sample adds less fresh information than an independent draw would.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] As a result, one must account for this correlation when assessing the accuracy of estimates from the chain.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In particular, positive autocorrelation in the chain increases the variance of estimators and slows the convergence of sample averages toward the true expectation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The effect of correlation on estimation can be quantified through the Markov chain central limit theorem.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For a chain targeting a distribution with variance $\sigma ^{2}$ , the variance of the sample mean after N steps is approximately ${\sigma ^{2}}{\big /}N_{\text{eff}}$ , where $N_{\text{eff}}$ is an effective sample size smaller than N .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The term in parentheses, $1+2\sum _{k=1}^{\infty }\rho _{k}$ , is often called the integrated autocorrelation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When the chain has no autocorrelation ( $\rho _{k}=0$ for all $k\geq 1$ ), this factor equals 1, and one recovers the usual $\sigma ^{2}/N$ variance for independent samples.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If the chain's samples are highly correlated, the sum of autocorrelations is large, leading to a much bigger variance for ${\bar {X}}_{N}$ than in the independent case.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The effective sample size $N_{\text{eff}}$ is a useful diagnostic that translates the autocorrelation in a chain into an equivalent number of independent samples.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] so that $N_{\text{eff}}$ is the number of independent draws that would yield the same estimation precision as the N dependent draws from the Markov chain.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For example, if $1+2\sum _{k=1}^{\infty }\rho _{k}=5$ , then $N_{\text{eff}}=N/5$ , meaning the chain of length N carries information equivalent to $N/5$ independent samples.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In an ideal scenario with no correlation, $\rho _{k}=0$ and thus $N_{\text{eff}}\approx N$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] But in a poorly mixing chain with strong autocorrelation, $N_{\text{eff}}$ can be much smaller than N .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In practice, monitoring the ESS for each parameter is a way to gauge how much correlation is present: a low ESS indicates that many more iterations may be needed to achieve a desired effective sample of independent draws.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] One way to address this problem could be shortening the steps of the walker, so that it does not continuously try to exit the highest probability region, though this way the process would be highly autocorrelated and expensive (i.e. many steps would be required for an accurate result).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] More sophisticated methods such as Hamiltonian Monte Carlo and the Wang and Landau algorithm use various ways of reducing this autocorrelation, while managing to keep the process in the regions that give a higher contribution to the integral.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These algorithms usually rely on a more complicated theory and are harder to implement, but they usually converge faster.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] We outline several general strategies such as reparameterization, adaptive proposal tuning, parameter blocking, and overrelaxation that help reduce correlation and improve sampling efficiency within the standard MCMC framework.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] One way to reduce autocorrelation is to reformulate or reparameterize the statistical model so that the posterior geometry leads to more efficient sampling.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] By changing the coordinate system or using alternative variable definitions, one can often lessen correlations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For example, in Bayesian hierarchical modeling, a non-centered parameterization can be used in place of the standard (centered) formulation to avoid extreme posterior correlations between latent and higher-level parameters.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This involves expressing latent variables in terms of independent auxiliary variables, dramatically improving mixing.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Such reparameterization strategies are commonly employed in both Gibbs sampling and Metropolis–Hastings algorithm to enhance convergence and reduce autocorrelation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Another approach to reducing correlation is to improve the MCMC proposal mechanism.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In Metropolis–Hastings algorithm, step size tuning is critical: if the proposed steps are too small, the sampler moves slowly and produces highly correlated samples; if the steps are too large, many proposals are rejected, resulting in repeated values.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Adjusting the proposal step size during an initial testing phase helps find a balance where the sampler explores the space efficiently without too many rejections.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Adaptive MCMC methods modify proposal distributions based on the chain's past samples.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For instance, the adaptive Metropolis algorithm updates the Gaussian proposal distribution using the full information accumulated from the chain so far, allowing the proposal to adapt over time.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Parameter blocking is a technique that reduces autocorrelation in MCMC by updating parameters jointly rather than one at a time.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When parameters exhibit strong posterior correlations, one-by-one updates can lead to poor mixing and slow exploration of the target distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] By identifying and sampling blocks of correlated parameters together, the sampler can more effectively traverse high-density regions of the posterior.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Parameter blocking is commonly used in both Gibbs sampling and Metropolis–Hastings algorithms.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In blocked Gibbs sampling, entire groups of variables are updated conditionally at each step.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In Metropolis–Hastings, multivariate proposals enable joint updates (i.e., updates of multiple parameters at once using a vector-valued proposal distribution, typically a multivariate Gaussian), though they often require careful tuning of the proposal covariance matrix.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Overrelaxation is a technique to reduce autocorrelation between successive samples by proposing new samples that are negatively correlated with the current state.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This helps the chain explore the posterior more efficiently, especially in high-dimensional Gaussian models or when using Gibbs sampling.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The basic idea is to reflect the current sample across the conditional mean, producing proposals that retain the correct stationary distribution but with reduced serial dependence.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Overrelaxation is particularly effective when combined with Gaussian conditional distributions, where exact reflection or partial overrelaxation can be analytically implemented.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Interacting MCMC methodologies are a class of mean-field particle methods for obtaining random samples from a sequence of probability distributions with an increasing level of sampling complexity.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In principle, any Markov chain Monte Carlo sampler can be turned into an interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo sampler.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers can be interpreted as a way to run in parallel a sequence of Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For instance, interacting simulated annealing algorithms are based on independent Metropolis–Hastings moves interacting sequentially with a selection-resampling type mechanism.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In contrast to traditional Markov chain Monte Carlo methods, the precision parameter of this class of interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers is *only* related to the number of interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo samplers.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] These advanced particle methodologies belong to the class of Feynman–Kac particle models, also called Sequential Monte Carlo or particle filter methods in Bayesian inference and signal processing communities.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Interacting Markov chain Monte Carlo methods can also be interpreted as a mutation-selection genetic particle algorithm with Markov chain Monte Carlo mutations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The quasi-Monte Carlo method is an analog to the normal Monte Carlo method that uses low-discrepancy sequences instead of random numbers.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] It yields an integration error that decays faster than that of true random sampling, as quantified by the Koksma–Hlawka inequality.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Empirically it allows the reduction of both estimation error and convergence time by an order of magnitude.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Markov chain quasi-Monte Carlo methods such as the Array–RQMC method combine randomized quasi–Monte Carlo and Markov chain simulation by simulating n chains simultaneously in a way that better approximates the true distribution of the chain than with ordinary MCMC.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In empirical experiments, the variance of the average of a function of the state sometimes converges at rate $O(n^{-2})$ or even faster, instead of the $O(n^{-1})$ Monte Carlo rate.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] MCMC methods are primarily used for calculating numerical approximations of multi-dimensional integrals, for example in Bayesian statistics, computational physics, computational biology and computational linguistics.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In Bayesian statistics, Markov chain Monte Carlo methods are typically used to calculate moments and credible intervals of posterior probability distributions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The use of MCMC methods makes it possible to compute large hierarchical models that require integrations over hundreds to thousands of unknown parameters.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Many contemporary research problems in statistical physics can be addressed by approximate solutions using Monte Carlo simulation, which provides valuable insights into the properties of complex systems.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Monte Carlo methods are fundamental in computational physics, astrophysics, physical chemistry, and related disciplines, with broad applications including medical physics, where they are employed to model radiation transport for radiation dosimetry calculations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Instead of exhaustively analyzing all possible system states, the Monte Carlo method randomly examines a subset of them to form a representative sample, and yields accurate approximations of the system's characteristic properties.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] As the number of sampled states increases, the error can be further reduced to a lower level.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Langevin Dynamics are typically used in complex distribution sampling and generative modeling, via an MCMC procedure.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Specifically, given the probability density function $p(x)$ , we use its log gradient $\nabla _{x}\log p(x)$ as the score function and start from a prior distribution $x_{0}\sim p_{0}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] When $\epsilon \rightarrow 0$ and $K\rightarrow \infty$ , $x_{K}$ converges to a sample from the target distribution $p(x)$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] For some complex distribution, if we know its probability density function but find it difficult to directly sample from it, we can apply Langevin Dynamics as an alternate.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] However, in most cases, especially generative modeling, usually we do not know the exact probability density function of the target distribution we wish to sample from, neither the score function $\nabla _{x}\log p(x)$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In this case, score matching methods provide feasible solutions, minimizing the Fisher information metric between a parameterized score-based model $s_{\theta }(x)$ and the score function without knowing the ground-truth data score.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The score function can be estimated on a training dataset by stochastic gradient descent.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In real cases, however, the training data only takes a small region of the target distribution, and the estimated score functions are inaccurate in other low density regions with fewer available data examples.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] To overcome this challenge, denoising score matching methods perturb the available data examples with noise of different scales, which can improve the coverage of low density regions, and use them as the training dataset for the score-base model.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Note that the choice of noise scales is tricky, as too large noise will corrupt the original data, while too small noise will not populate the original data to those low density regions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Thus, carefully crafted noise schedules are applied for higher quality generation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Usually it is not hard to construct a Markov chain with the desired properties.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The more difficult problem is to determine (1) when to start collecting statistics and (2) how many steps are needed to converge to the stationary distribution within an acceptable error.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Fortunately, there are a variety of practical diagnostics to empirically assess convergence.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Formally, let $\pi$ denote the stationary distribution and $P^{t}(x,\cdot )$ the distribution of the Markov chain after t steps starting from state x .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] A chain is said to mix rapidly if $d_{\text{TV}}(P^{t}(x,\cdot ),\pi )\leq \epsilon$ for all $x\in {\mathcal {X}}$ within a small number of steps t under a pre-defined tolerance $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In other words, the stationary distribution is reached quickly starting from an arbitrary position, and the minimum such t is known as the mixing time.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In practice, however, the total variation distance is generally intractable to compute, especially in high-dimensional problems or when the stationary distribution is only known up to a normalizing constant (as in most Bayesian applications).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Gelman-Rubin statistic, also known as the **potential scale reduction factor (PSRF)**, evaluates MCMC convergence by sampling multiple independent Markov chains and comparing within-chain and between-chain variances.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If all chains have converged to the same stationary distribution, the between-chain and within-chain variances should be similar, and thus the PSRF must approach 1.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] In practice, a value of $<1.1$ is often taken as evidence of convergence.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Higher values suggest that the chains are still exploring different parts of the target distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Geweke diagnostic examines whether the distribution of samples in the early part of the Markov chain is statistically indistinguishable from the distribution in a later part.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Since MCMC samples are autocorrelated, a simple comparison of sample means is insufficient.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Instead, the difference in means is standardized using an estimator of the spectral density at zero frequency, which accounts for the long-range dependencies in the chain.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where ${\hat {S}}(0)$ is an estimate of the long-run variance (i.e., the spectral density at frequency zero), commonly estimated using Newey-West estimators or batch means.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Under the null hypothesis of convergence, the statistic Z follows an approximately standard normal distribution $Z\sim {\mathcal {N}}(0,1)$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If $|Z|>1.96$ , the null hypothesis is rejected at the 5% significance level, suggesting that the chain has not yet reached stationarity.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Heidelberger-Welch diagnostic is grounded in spectral analysis and Brownian motion theory, and is particularly useful in the early stages of simulation to determine appropriate burn-in and stopping time.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The diagnostic consists of two components, a **stationarity test** that assesses whether the Markov chain has reached a steady-state, and a **half-width test** that determines whether the estimated expectation is within a user-specified precision.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Let $\{X_{t}\}_{t=1}^{n}$ be the output of an MCMC simulation for a scalar function $g(X_{t})$ , and $g_{1},g_{2},\dots ,g_{n}$ the evaluations of the function g over the chain.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where ${\bar {g}}_{n}={\frac {1}{n}}\sum _{i=1}^{n}g_{i}$ is the sample mean and ${\hat {S}}(0)$ is an estimate of the spectral density at frequency zero.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Under the null hypothesis of convergence, the process $B_{n}(t)$ converges in distribution to a Brownian bridge.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] This statistic is compared against known critical values from the Brownian bridge distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If the null hypothesis is rejected, the first 10% of the samples are discarded and the test can be repeated on the remaining chain until either stationarity is accepted or 50% of the chain is discarded.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Once stationarity is accepted, the second part of the diagnostic checks whether the Monte Carlo estimator is accurate enough for practical use.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where ${\hat {\sigma }}^{2}$ is an estimate of the variance of $g(X)$ , $t_{\alpha /2,\nu }$ is the Student's t critical value at confidence level $1-\alpha$ and degrees of freedom $\nu$ , n is the number of samples used.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] If the half-width is smaller than a user-defined tolerance (e.g., 0.05), the chain is considered long enough to estimate the expectation reliably.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Otherwise, the simulation should be extended.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The Raftery-Lewis diagnostic is specifically designed to assess how many iterations are needed to estimate quantiles or tail probabilities of the target distribution with a desired accuracy and confidence.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Unlike Gelman-Rubin or Geweke diagnostics, which are based on assessing convergence to the entire distribution, the Raftery-Lewis diagnostic is goal-oriented as it provides estimates for the number of samples required to estimate a specific quantile of interest within a desired margin of error.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Let q denote the desired quantile (e.g., 0.025) of a real-valued function $g(X)$ : in other words, the goal is to find u such that $P(g(X)\leq u)=q$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] Suppose we wish to estimate this quantile such that the estimate falls within margin $\varepsilon$ of the true value with probability $1-\alpha$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where $I(\cdot )$ is the indicator function.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] The sequence $\{W_{n}\}$ is treated as a realization from a two-state Markov chain.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] While this may not be strictly true, it is often a good approximation in practice.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/markov-chain-monte-carlo] where $\Phi ^{-1}(\cdot )$ is the standard normal quantile function.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] In statistics and statistical physics, the **Metropolis–Hastings algorithm** is a Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) method for obtaining a sequence of random samples from a probability distribution from which direct sampling is difficult.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] New samples are added to the sequence in two steps: first a new sample is proposed based on the previous sample, then the proposed sample is either added to the sequence or rejected depending on the value of the probability distribution at that point.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The resulting sequence can be used to approximate the distribution (e.g. to generate a histogram) or to compute an integral (e.g. an expected value).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Metropolis–Hastings and other MCMC algorithms are generally used for sampling from multi-dimensional distributions, especially when the number of dimensions is high.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For single-dimensional distributions, there are usually other methods (e.g. adaptive rejection sampling) that can directly return independent samples from the distribution, and these are free from the problem of autocorrelated samples that is inherent in MCMC methods.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The algorithm is named in part for Nicholas Metropolis, the first coauthor of a 1953 paper, entitled *Equation of State Calculations by Fast Computing Machines*, with Arianna W.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For many years the algorithm was known simply as the *Metropolis algorithm*.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The paper proposed the algorithm for the case of symmetrical proposal distributions, but in 1970, W.K.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Hastings extended it to the more general case.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The generalized method was eventually identified by both names, although the first use of the term "Metropolis-Hastings algorithm" is unclear.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Some controversy exists with regard to credit for development of the Metropolis algorithm.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Metropolis, who was familiar with the computational aspects of the method, had coined the term "Monte Carlo" in an earlier article with Stanisław Ulam, and led the group in the Theoretical Division that designed and built the MANIAC I computer used in the experiments in 1952.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] However, prior to 2003 there was no detailed account of the algorithm's development.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Shortly before his death, Marshall Rosenbluth attended a 2003 conference at LANL marking the 50th anniversary of the 1953 publication.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] At this conference, Rosenbluth described the algorithm and its development in a presentation titled "Genesis of the Monte Carlo Algorithm for Statistical Mechanics".
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Further historical clarification is made by Gubernatis in a 2005 journal article recounting the 50th anniversary conference.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Rosenbluth makes it clear that he and his wife Arianna did the work, and that Metropolis played no role in the development other than providing computer time.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This contradicts an account by Edward Teller, who states in his memoirs that the five authors of the 1953 article worked together for "days (and nights)".
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] In contrast, the detailed account by Rosenbluth credits Teller with a crucial but early suggestion to "take advantage of statistical mechanics and take ensemble averages instead of following detailed kinematics".
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This, says Rosenbluth, started him thinking about the generalized Monte Carlo approach – a topic which he says he had discussed often with John Von Neumann.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Arianna Rosenbluth recounted (to Gubernatis in 2003) that Augusta Teller started the computer work, but that Arianna herself took it over and wrote the code from scratch.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] In an oral history recorded shortly before his death, Rosenbluth again credits Teller with posing the original problem, himself with solving it, and Arianna with programming the computer.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The Metropolis–Hastings algorithm can draw samples from any probability distribution with probability density $P(x)$ , provided that we know a function $f(x)$ proportional to the density P and the values of $f(x)$ can be calculated.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The requirement that $f(x)$ must only be proportional to the density, rather than exactly equal to it, makes the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm particularly useful, because it removes the need to calculate the density's normalization factor, which is often extremely difficult in practice.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The Metropolis–Hastings algorithm generates a sequence of sample values in such a way that, as more and more sample values are produced, the distribution of values more closely approximates the desired distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] These sample values are produced iteratively in such a way, that the distribution of the next sample depends only on the current sample value, which makes the sequence of samples a Markov chain.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Specifically, at each iteration, the algorithm proposes a candidate for the next sample value based on the current sample value.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Then, with some probability, the candidate is either accepted, in which case the candidate value is used in the next iteration, or it is rejected in which case the candidate value is discarded, and the current value is reused in the next iteration.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The probability of acceptance is determined by comparing the values of the function $f(x)$ of the current and candidate sample values with respect to the desired distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The method used to propose new candidates is characterized by the probability distribution $g(x\mid y)$ (sometimes written $Q(x\mid y)$ ) of a new proposed sample x given the previous sample y .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This is called the *proposal density*, *proposal function*, or *jumping distribution*.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] A common choice for $g(x\mid y)$ is a Gaussian distribution centered at y , so that points closer to y are more likely to be visited next, making the sequence of samples into a Gaussian random walk.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] In the original paper by Metropolis et al.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] (1953), $g(x\mid y)$ was suggested to be a uniform distribution limited to some maximum distance from y .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] More complicated proposal functions are also possible, such as those of Hamiltonian Monte Carlo, Langevin Monte Carlo, or preconditioned Crank–Nicolson.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For the purpose of illustration, the Metropolis algorithm, a special case of the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm where the proposal function is symmetric, is described below.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Let $f(x)$ be a function that is proportional to the desired probability density function $P(x)$ (a.k.a. a target distribution).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This algorithm proceeds by randomly attempting to move about the sample space, sometimes accepting the moves and sometimes remaining in place. $P(x)$ at specific point x is proportional to the iterations spent on the point by the algorithm.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Note that the acceptance ratio $\alpha$ indicates how probable the new proposed sample is with respect to the current sample, according to the distribution whose density is $P(x)$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] If we attempt to move to a point that is more probable than the existing point (i.e. a point in a higher-density region of $P(x)$ corresponding to an $\alpha >1\geq u$ ), we will always accept the move.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] However, if we attempt to move to a less probable point, we will sometimes reject the move, and the larger the relative drop in probability, the more likely we are to reject the new point.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Thus, we will tend to stay in (and return large numbers of samples from) high-density regions of $P(x)$ , while only occasionally visiting low-density regions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Intuitively, this is why this algorithm works and returns samples that follow the desired distribution with density $P(x)$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] On the other hand, most simple rejection sampling methods suffer from the "curse of dimensionality", where the probability of rejection increases exponentially as a function of the number of dimensions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Metropolis–Hastings, along with other MCMC methods, do not have this problem to such a degree, and thus are often the only solutions available when the number of dimensions of the distribution to be sampled is high.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] As a result, MCMC methods are often the methods of choice for producing samples from hierarchical Bayesian models and other high-dimensional statistical models used nowadays in many disciplines.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] In multivariate distributions, the classic Metropolis–Hastings algorithm as described above involves choosing a new multi-dimensional sample point.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] When the number of dimensions is high, finding the suitable jumping distribution to use can be difficult, as the different individual dimensions behave in very different ways, and the jumping width (see above) must be "just right" for all dimensions at once to avoid excessively slow mixing.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] An alternative approach that often works better in such situations, known as Gibbs sampling, involves choosing a new sample for each dimension separately from the others, rather than choosing a sample for all dimensions at once.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] That way, the problem of sampling from potentially high-dimensional space will be reduced to a collection of problems to sample from small dimensionality.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This is especially applicable when the multivariate distribution is composed of a set of individual random variables in which each variable is conditioned on only a small number of other variables, as is the case in most typical hierarchical models.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The individual variables are then sampled one at a time, with each variable conditioned on the most recent values of all the others.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The purpose of the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm is to generate a collection of states according to a desired distribution $P(x)$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] To accomplish this, the algorithm uses a Markov process, which asymptotically reaches a unique stationary distribution $\pi (x)$ such that $\pi (x)=P(x)$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] A Markov process is uniquely defined by its transition probabilities $P(x'\mid x)$ , the probability of transitioning from any given state x to any other given state $x'$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] *Uniqueness of stationary distribution*: the stationary distribution $\pi (x)$ must be unique.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This is guaranteed by ergodicity of the Markov process, which requires that every state must (1) be aperiodic—the system does not return to the same state at fixed intervals; and (2) be positive recurrent—the expected number of steps for returning to the same state is finite.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The Metropolis–Hastings algorithm involves designing a Markov process (by constructing transition probabilities) that fulfills the two above conditions, such that its stationary distribution $\pi (x)$ is chosen to be $P(x)$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The approach is to separate the transition in two sub-steps; the proposal and the acceptance-rejection.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The proposal distribution $g(x'\mid x)$ is the conditional probability of proposing a state $x'$ given x , and the acceptance distribution $A(x',x)$ is the probability to accept the proposed state $x'$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The next step in the derivation is to choose an acceptance ratio that fulfills the condition above.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For this Metropolis acceptance ratio A , either $A(x',x)=1$ or $A(x,x')=1$ and, either way, the condition is satisfied.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] 3. if $u>A(x',x_{t})$ , then *reject* the new state, and copy the old state forward $x_{t+1}=x_{t}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Provided that specified conditions are met, the empirical distribution of saved states $x_{0},\ldots ,x_{T}$ will approach $P(x)$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The number of iterations ( T ) required to effectively estimate $P(x)$ depends on the number of factors, including the relationship between $P(x)$ and the proposal distribution and the desired accuracy of estimation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For distribution on discrete state spaces, it has to be of the order of the autocorrelation time of the Markov process.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] An accessible account of the convergence theory for Metropolis–Hastings is given in.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] It is important to notice that it is not clear, in a general problem, which distribution $g(x'\mid x)$ one should use or the number of iterations necessary for proper estimation; both are free parameters of the method, which must be adjusted to the particular problem in hand.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] A common use of Metropolis–Hastings algorithm is to compute an integral.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Specifically, consider a space $\Omega \subset \mathbb {R}$ and a probability distribution $P(x)$ over $\Omega$ , $x\in \Omega$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] where $A(x)$ is a (measurable) function of interest.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] For example, consider a statistic $E(x)$ and its probability distribution $P(E)$ , which is a marginal distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Suppose that the goal is to estimate $P(E)$ for E on the tail of $P(E)$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] and, thus, estimating $P(E)$ can be accomplished by estimating the expected value of the indicator function $A_{E}(x)\equiv \mathbf {1} _{E}(x)$ , which is 1 when $E(x)\in [E,E+\Delta E]$ and zero otherwise.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Because E is on the tail of $P(E)$ , the probability to draw a state x with $E(x)$ on the tail of $P(E)$ is proportional to $P(E)$ , which is small by definition.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The Metropolis–Hastings algorithm can be used here to sample (rare) states more likely and thus increase the number of samples used to estimate $P(E)$ on the tails.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This can be done e.g. by using a sampling distribution $\pi (x)$ to favor those states (e.g. $\pi (x)\propto e^{aE}$ with $a>0$ ).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Suppose that the most recent value sampled is $x_{t}$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] is the ratio of the proposal density in two directions (from $x_{t}$ to $x'$ and conversely).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This is equal to 1 if the proposal density is symmetric.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] Then the new state $x_{t+1}$ is chosen according to the following rules.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The Markov chain is started from an arbitrary initial value $x_{0}$ , and the algorithm is run for many iterations until this initial state is "forgotten".
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] These samples, which are discarded, are known as *burn-in*.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The remaining set of accepted values of x represent a sample from the distribution $P(x)$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The algorithm works best if the proposal density matches the shape of the target distribution $P(x)$ , from which direct sampling is difficult, that is $g(x'\mid x_{t})\approx P(x')$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] If a Gaussian proposal density g is used, the variance parameter $\sigma ^{2}$ has to be tuned during the burn-in period.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] This is usually done by calculating the *acceptance rate*, which is the fraction of proposed samples that is accepted in a window of the last N samples.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] The desired acceptance rate depends on the target distribution, however it has been shown theoretically that the ideal acceptance rate for a one-dimensional Gaussian distribution is about 50%, decreasing to about 23% for an N -dimensional Gaussian target distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] These guidelines can work well when sampling from sufficiently regular Bayesian posteriors as they often follow a multivariate normal distribution as can be established using the Bernstein–von Mises theorem.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] If $\sigma ^{2}$ is too small, the chain will *mix slowly* (i.e., the acceptance rate will be high, but successive samples will move around the space slowly, and the chain will converge only slowly to $P(x)$ ).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] On the other hand, if $\sigma ^{2}$ is too large, the acceptance rate will be very low because the proposals are likely to land in regions of much lower probability density, so $a_{1}$ will be very small, and again the chain will converge very slowly.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] One typically tunes the proposal distribution so that the algorithms accepts on the order of 30% of all samples – in line with the theoretical estimates mentioned in the previous paragraph.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/metropolis-hastings-algorithm] MCMC can be used to draw samples from the posterior distribution of a statistical model.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are mainly used in three distinct problem classes: optimization, numerical integration, and non-uniform random variate generation, available for modeling phenomena with significant input uncertainties, e.g. risk assessments for nuclear power plants.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are often implemented using computer simulations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] They can provide approximate solutions to problems too complex for mathematical analysis.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The name comes from the Monte Carlo Casino in Monaco, where the primary developer of the method, mathematician Stanisław Ulam, was inspired by his uncle's gambling habits.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are widely used in various fields of science, engineering, and mathematics, such as physics, chemistry, biology, statistics, artificial intelligence, finance, and cryptography.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] They have also been applied to social sciences, such as sociology, psychology, and political science.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods have been recognized as one of the most important and influential ideas of the 20th century, and they have enabled many scientific and technological breakthroughs.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods also have some limitations and challenges, such as the trade-off between accuracy and computational cost, the curse of dimensionality, the reliability of random number generators, and the verification and validation of the results.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Generate inputs randomly from a probability distribution over the domain.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Perform a deterministic computation of the outputs.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] For example, consider a quadrant (circular sector) inscribed in a unit square.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Uniformly scatter a given number of points over the square.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Count the number of points inside the quadrant, i.e. having a distance from the origin of less than 1.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The ratio of the inside-count and the total-sample-count is an estimate of the ratio of the two areas, ⁠π/4⁠.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] In this procedure, the domain of inputs is the square that circumscribes the quadrant.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] One can generate random inputs by scattering grains over the square, then performing a computation on each input to test whether it falls within the quadrant.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Aggregating the results yields our final result, the approximation of π.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The approximation improves as more points are randomly placed in the whole square.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Uses of Monte Carlo methods require large amounts of random numbers, and their use benefitted greatly from pseudorandom number generators, which are far quicker to use than the tables of random numbers that had been previously employed.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are often used in physical and mathematical problems and are most useful when it is difficult or impossible to use other approaches.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are mainly used in three problem classes: optimization, numerical integration, and generating draws from a probability distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Other examples include modeling phenomena with significant uncertainty in inputs such as the calculation of risk in business and, in mathematics, evaluation of multidimensional definite integrals with complicated boundary conditions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] In application to systems engineering problems (space, oil exploration, aircraft design, etc.), Monte Carlo–based predictions of failure, cost overruns and schedule overruns are routinely better than human intuition or alternative "soft" methods.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] In principle, Monte Carlo methods can be used to solve any problem having a probabilistic interpretation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] By the law of large numbers, integrals described by the expected value of some random variable can be approximated by taking the empirical mean (a.k.a. the 'sample mean') of independent samples of the variable.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] When the probability distribution of the variable is parameterized, mathematicians often use a Markov chain Monte Carlo (MCMC) sampler.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The central idea is to design a judicious Markov chain model with a prescribed stationary probability distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] That is, in the limit, the samples being generated by the MCMC method will be samples from the desired (target) distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] By the ergodic theorem, the stationary distribution is approximated by the empirical measures of the random states of the MCMC sampler.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] In other problems, the objective is generating draws from a sequence of probability distributions satisfying a nonlinear evolution equation.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] These flows of probability distributions can always be interpreted as the distributions of the random states of a Markov process whose transition probabilities depend on the distributions of the current random states (see McKean–Vlasov processes, nonlinear filtering equation).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] In other instances, a flow of probability distributions with an increasing level of sampling complexity arise (path spaces models with an increasing time horizon, Boltzmann–Gibbs measures associated with decreasing temperature parameters, and many others).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] These models can also be seen as the evolution of the law of the random states of a nonlinear Markov chain.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] A natural way to simulate these sophisticated nonlinear Markov processes is to sample multiple copies of the process, replacing in the evolution equation the unknown distributions of the random states by the sampled empirical measures.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] In contrast with traditional Monte Carlo and MCMC methodologies, these mean-field particle techniques rely on sequential interacting samples.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The terminology *mean field* reflects the fact that each of the *samples* (a.k.a. particles, individuals, walkers, agents, creatures, or phenotypes) interacts with the empirical measures of the process.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] When the size of the system tends to infinity, these random empirical measures converge to the deterministic distribution of the random states of the nonlinear Markov chain, so that the statistical interaction between particles vanishes.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Suppose one wants to know the expected value $\mu$ of a population (and knows that $\mu$ exists), but does not have a formula available to compute it.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The simple Monte Carlo method gives an estimate for $\mu$ by running n simulations and averaging the simulations' results.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] It has no restrictions on the probability distribution of the inputs to the simulations, requiring only that the inputs are randomly generated and are independent of each other and that $\mu$ exists.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] A sufficiently large n will produce a value for m that is arbitrarily close to $\mu$ ; more formally, it will be the case that, for any $\epsilon >0$ , $|\mu -m|\leq \epsilon$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Suppose we want to know how many times we should expect to throw three eight-sided dice for the total of the dice throws to be at least T .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The dice throws are randomly distributed and independent of each other.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] If n is large enough, m will be within $\epsilon$ of $\mu$ for any $\epsilon >0$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Choose the desired confidence level – the percent chance that, when the Monte Carlo algorithm completes, m is indeed within $\epsilon$ of $\mu$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Let z be the z -score corresponding to that confidence level.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Let $s^{2}$ be the estimated variance, sometimes called the "sample" variance; it is the variance of the results obtained from a relatively small number k of "sample" simulations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Note that, when the algorithm completes, $m_{k}$ is the mean of the k results.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] If $n\leq k$ , then $m_{k}=m$ ; sufficient sample simulations were done to ensure that $m_{k}$ is within $\epsilon$ of $\mu$ .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] An alternative formula can be used in the special case where all simulation results are bounded above and below.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Choose a value for $\epsilon$ that is twice the maximum allowed difference between $\mu$ and m .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Let $0<\delta <100$ be the desired confidence level, expressed as a percentage.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Let every simulation result $r_{1},r_{2},\ldots ,r_{i},\ldots ,r_{n}$ be such that $a\leq r_{i}\leq b$ for finite a and b .
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Despite its conceptual and algorithmic simplicity, the computational cost associated with a Monte Carlo simulation can be staggeringly high.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] In general the method requires many samples to get a good approximation, which may incur an arbitrarily large total runtime if the processing time of a single sample is high.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Although this is a severe limitation in very complex problems, the embarrassingly parallel nature of the algorithm allows this large cost to be reduced (perhaps to a feasible level) through parallel computing strategies in local processors, clusters, cloud computing, GPU, FPGA, etc.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Before the Monte Carlo method was developed, simulations tested a previously understood deterministic problem, and statistical sampling was used to estimate uncertainties in the simulations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulations invert this approach, solving deterministic problems using probabilistic metaheuristics (see simulated annealing).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] An early variant of the Monte Carlo method was devised to solve the Buffon's needle problem, in which π can be estimated by dropping needles on a floor made of parallel equidistant strips.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] In the 1930s, Enrico Fermi first experimented with the Monte Carlo method while studying neutron diffusion, but he did not publish this work.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] In the late 1940s, Stanisław Ulam invented the modern version of the Markov Chain Monte Carlo method while he was working on nuclear weapons projects at the Los Alamos National Laboratory.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] In 1946, nuclear weapons physicists at Los Alamos were investigating neutron diffusion in the core of a nuclear weapon.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Being secret, the work of von Neumann and Ulam required a code name.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] A colleague of von Neumann and Ulam, Nicholas Metropolis, suggested using the name *Monte Carlo*, which refers to the Monte Carlo Casino in Monaco where Ulam's uncle would borrow money from relatives to gamble.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods were central to the simulations required for further postwar development of nuclear weapons, including the design of the H-bomb, though severely limited by the computational tools at the time.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Von Neumann, Nicholas Metropolis and others programmed the ENIAC computer to perform the first fully automated Monte Carlo calculations, of a fission weapon core, in the spring of 1948.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] In the 1950s Monte Carlo methods were used at Los Alamos for the development of the hydrogen bomb, and became popularized in the fields of physics, physical chemistry, and operations research.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Air Force were two of the major organizations responsible for funding and disseminating information on Monte Carlo methods during this time, and they began to find a wide application in many different fields.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The theory of more sophisticated mean-field type particle Monte Carlo methods had certainly started by the mid-1960s, with the work of Henry P.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] McKean Jr. on Markov interpretations of a class of nonlinear parabolic partial differential equations arising in fluid mechanics.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] An earlier pioneering article by Theodore E.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Harris and Herman Kahn, published in 1951, used mean-field genetic-type Monte Carlo methods for estimating particle transmission energies.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Mean-field genetic type Monte Carlo methodologies are also used as heuristic natural search algorithms (a.k.a. metaheuristic) in evolutionary computing.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The origins of these mean-field computational techniques can be traced to 1950 and 1954 with the work of Alan Turing on genetic type mutation-selection learning machines and the articles by Nils Aall Barricelli at the Institute for Advanced Study in Princeton, New Jersey.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Quantum Monte Carlo, and more specifically diffusion Monte Carlo methods can also be interpreted as a mean-field particle Monte Carlo approximation of Feynman–Kac path integrals.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The origins of Quantum Monte Carlo methods are often attributed to Enrico Fermi and Robert Richtmyer who developed in 1948 a mean-field particle interpretation of neutron-chain reactions, but the first heuristic-like and genetic type particle algorithm (a.k.a.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Resampled or Reconfiguration Monte Carlo methods) for estimating ground state energies of quantum systems (in reduced matrix models) is due to Jack H.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] In molecular chemistry, the use of genetic heuristic-like particle methodologies (a.k.a. pruning and enrichment strategies) can be traced back to 1955 with the seminal work of Marshall N.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The use of sequential Monte Carlo in advanced signal processing and Bayesian inference is more recent.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] It was in 1993, that Gordon et al., published in their seminal work the first application of a Monte Carlo resampling algorithm in Bayesian statistical inference.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The authors named their algorithm 'the bootstrap filter', and demonstrated that compared to other filtering methods, their bootstrap algorithm does not require any assumption about that state-space or the noise of the system.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Another pioneering article in this field was Genshiro Kitagawa's, on a related "Monte Carlo filter", and the ones by Pierre Del Moral and Himilcon Carvalho, Pierre Del Moral, André Monin and Gérard Salut on particle filters published in the mid-1990s.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Particle filters were also developed in signal processing in 1989–1992 by P.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Salut in the LAAS-CNRS in a series of restricted and classified research reports with STCAN (Service Technique des Constructions et Armes Navales), the IT company DIGILOG, and the LAAS-CNRS (the Laboratory for Analysis and Architecture of Systems) on radar/sonar and GPS signal processing problems.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] These Sequential Monte Carlo methodologies can be interpreted as an acceptance-rejection sampler equipped with an interacting recycling mechanism.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The mathematical foundations and the first rigorous analysis of these particle algorithms were written by Pierre Del Moral in 1996.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Branching type particle methodologies with varying population sizes were also developed in the end of the 1990s by Dan Crisan, Jessica Gaines and Terry Lyons, and by Dan Crisan, Pierre Del Moral and Terry Lyons.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Further developments in this field were described in 1999 to 2001 by P.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] There is no consensus on how *Monte Carlo* should be defined.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] For example, Ripley defines most probabilistic modeling as *stochastic simulation*, with *Monte Carlo* being reserved for Monte Carlo integration and Monte Carlo statistical tests.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Sawilowsky distinguishes between a simulation, a Monte Carlo method, and a Monte Carlo simulation: a simulation is a fictitious representation of reality, a Monte Carlo method is a technique that can be used to solve a mathematical or statistical problem.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] A Monte Carlo simulation uses repeated sampling to obtain the statistical properties of some phenomena.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Kalos and Whitlock point out that such distinctions are not always easy to maintain.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] For example, the emission of radiation from atoms is a natural stochastic process.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] It can be simulated directly, or its average behavior can be described by stochastic equations that can themselves be solved using Monte Carlo methods.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] "Indeed, the same computer code can be viewed simultaneously as a 'natural simulation' or as a solution of the equations by natural sampling." Convergence of the Monte Carlo simulation can be checked with the Gelman-Rubin statistic.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The main idea behind this method is that the results are computed based on repeated random sampling and statistical analysis.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo simulation is, in fact, random experimentations, in the case that, the results of these experiments are not well known.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulations are typically characterized by many unknown parameters, many of which are difficult to obtain experimentally.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulation methods do not always require truly random numbers to be useful (although, for some applications such as primality testing, unpredictability is vital).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Many of the most useful techniques use deterministic, pseudorandom sequences, making it easy to test and re-run simulations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The only quality usually necessary to make good simulations is for the pseudo-random sequence to appear "random enough" in a certain sense.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] What this means depends on the application, but typically they should pass a series of statistical tests.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Testing that the numbers are uniformly distributed or follow another desired distribution when a large enough number of elements of the sequence are considered is one of the simplest and most common ones.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Weak correlations between successive samples are also often desirable/necessary.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Pseudo-random number sampling algorithms are used to transform uniformly distributed pseudo-random numbers into numbers that are distributed according to a given probability distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Low-discrepancy sequences are often used instead of random sampling from a space as they ensure even coverage and normally have a faster order of convergence than Monte Carlo simulations using random or pseudorandom sequences.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Methods based on their use are called quasi-Monte Carlo methods.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] No statistically significant difference was found between models generated with typical pseudorandom number generators and RDRAND for trials consisting of the generation of 107 random numbers.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] There are ways of using probabilities that are definitely not Monte Carlo simulations – for example, deterministic modeling using single-point estimates.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Each uncertain variable within a model is assigned a "best guess" estimate.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Scenarios (such as best, worst, or most likely case) for each input variable are chosen and the results recorded.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] By contrast, Monte Carlo simulations sample from a probability distribution for each variable to produce hundreds or thousands of possible outcomes.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The results are analyzed to get probabilities of different outcomes occurring.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] This is because the "what if" analysis gives equal weight to all scenarios (see quantifying uncertainty in corporate finance), while the Monte Carlo method hardly samples in the very low probability regions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The samples in such regions are called "rare events".
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are especially useful for simulating phenomena with significant uncertainty in inputs and systems with many coupled degrees of freedom.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] In statistical physics, Monte Carlo molecular modeling is an alternative to computational molecular dynamics, and Monte Carlo methods are used to compute statistical field theories of simple particle and polymer systems.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Quantum Monte Carlo methods solve the many-body problem for quantum systems.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] In radiation materials science, the binary collision approximation for simulating ion implantation is usually based on a Monte Carlo approach to select the next colliding atom.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] In experimental particle physics, Monte Carlo methods are used for designing detectors, understanding their behavior and comparing experimental data to theory.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] In astrophysics, they are used in such diverse manners as to model both galaxy evolution and microwave radiation transmission through a rough planetary surface.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are also used in the ensemble models that form the basis of modern weather forecasting.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are widely used in engineering for sensitivity analysis and quantitative probabilistic analysis in process design.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The need arises from the interactive, co-linear and non-linear behavior of typical process simulations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The Intergovernmental Panel on Climate Change relies on Monte Carlo methods in probability density function analysis of radiative forcing.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are used in various fields of computational biology, for example for Bayesian inference in phylogeny, or for studying biological systems such as genomes, proteins, or membranes.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The systems can be studied in the coarse-grained or *ab initio* frameworks depending on the desired accuracy.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Computer simulations allow monitoring of the local environment of a particular molecule to see if some chemical reaction is happening for instance.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] In cases where it is not feasible to conduct a physical experiment, thought experiments can be conducted, e.g. breaking bonds, introducing impurities at specific sites, changing the local/global structure, or introducing external fields.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Path tracing, occasionally referred to as Monte Carlo ray tracing, renders a 3D scene by randomly tracing samples of possible light paths.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Repeated sampling of any given pixel will eventually cause the average of the samples to converge on the correct solution of the rendering equation, making it one of the most physically accurate 3D graphics rendering methods in existence.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The standards for Monte Carlo experiments in statistics were set by Sawilowsky.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] To provide implementations of hypothesis tests that are more efficient than exact tests such as permutation tests (which are often impossible to compute) while being more accurate than critical values for asymptotic distributions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] To provide a random sample from the posterior distribution in Bayesian inference.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] This sample then approximates and summarizes all the essential features of the posterior.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] To provide efficient random estimates of the Hessian matrix of the negative log-likelihood function that may be averaged to form an estimate of the Fisher information matrix.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are also a compromise between approximate randomization and permutation tests.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] An approximate randomization test is based on a specified subset of all permutations (which entails potentially enormous housekeeping of which permutations have been considered).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo approach is based on a specified number of randomly drawn permutations (exchanging a minor loss in precision if a permutation is drawn twice—or more frequently—for the efficiency of not having to track which permutations have already been selected).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods have been developed into a technique called Monte-Carlo tree search that is useful for searching for the best move in a game.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Possible moves are organized in a search tree and many random simulations are used to estimate the long-term potential of each move.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] A black box simulator represents the opponent's moves.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Expand the leaf node and choose one of its children.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Play a simulated game starting with that node.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Use the results of that simulated game to update the node and its ancestors.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The net effect, over the course of many simulated games, is that the value of a node representing a move will go up or down, hopefully corresponding to whether or not that node represents a good move.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo Tree Search has been used successfully to play games such as Go, Tantrix, Battleship, Havannah, and Arimaa.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The US Coast Guard utilizes Monte Carlo methods within its computer modeling software SAROPS in order to calculate the probable locations of vessels during search and rescue operations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Each simulation can generate as many as ten thousand data points that are randomly distributed based upon provided variables.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Search patterns are then generated based upon extrapolations of these data in order to optimize the probability of containment (POC) and the probability of detection (POD), which together will equal an overall probability of success (POS).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Ultimately this serves as a practical application of probability distribution in order to provide the swiftest and most expedient method of rescue, saving both lives and resources.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo simulation is commonly used to evaluate the risk and uncertainty that would affect the outcome of different decision options.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods in finance are often used to evaluate investments in projects at a business unit or corporate level, or other financial valuations.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] They can be used to model project schedules, where simulations aggregate estimates for worst-case, best-case, and most likely durations for each task to determine outcomes for the overall project.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods are also used in option pricing, default risk analysis.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Additionally, they can be used to estimate the financial impact of medical interventions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] A Monte Carlo approach was used for evaluating the potential value of a proposed program to help female petitioners in Wisconsin be successful in their applications for harassment and domestic abuse restraining orders.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] It was proposed to help women succeed in their petitions by providing them with greater advocacy thereby potentially reducing the risk of rape and physical assault.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] However, there were many variables in play that could not be estimated perfectly, including the effectiveness of restraining orders, the success rate of petitioners both with and without advocacy, and many others.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The study ran trials that varied these variables to come up with an overall estimate of the success level of the proposed program as a whole.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo approach had also been used to simulate the number of book publications based on book genre in Malaysia.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo simulation utilized previous published National Book publication data and book's price according to book genre in the local market.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The Monte Carlo results were used to determine what kind of book genre that Malaysians are fond of and was used to compare book publications between Malaysia and Japan.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Nassim Nicholas Taleb writes about Monte Carlo generators in his 2001 book *Fooled by Randomness* as a real instance of the reverse Turing test: a human can be declared unintelligent if their writing cannot be told apart from a generated one.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] In general, the Monte Carlo methods are used in mathematics to solve various problems by generating suitable random numbers (see also Random number generation) and observing that fraction of the numbers that obeys some property or properties.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The method is useful for obtaining numerical solutions to problems too complicated to solve analytically.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The most common application of the Monte Carlo method is Monte Carlo integration.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Deterministic numerical integration algorithms work well in a small number of dimensions, but encounter two problems when the functions have many variables.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] First, the number of function evaluations needed increases rapidly with the number of dimensions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] For example, if 10 evaluations provide adequate accuracy in one dimension, then 10100 points are needed for 100 dimensions—far too many to be computed.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] This is called the curse of dimensionality.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Second, the boundary of a multidimensional region may be very complicated, so it may not be feasible to reduce the problem to an iterated integral.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] 100 dimensions is by no means unusual, since in many physical problems, a "dimension" is equivalent to a degree of freedom.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Monte Carlo methods provide a way out of this exponential increase in computation time.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] As long as the function in question is reasonably well-behaved, it can be estimated by randomly selecting points in 100-dimensional space, and taking some kind of average of the function values at these points.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] By the central limit theorem, this method displays $\scriptstyle 1/{\sqrt {N}}$ convergence—i.e., quadrupling the number of sampled points halves the error, regardless of the number of dimensions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] A refinement of this method, known as importance sampling in statistics, involves sampling the points randomly, but more frequently where the integrand is large.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] To do this precisely one would have to already know the integral, but one can approximate the integral by an integral of a similar function or use adaptive routines such as stratified sampling, recursive stratified sampling, adaptive umbrella sampling or the VEGAS algorithm.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] A similar approach, the quasi-Monte Carlo method, uses low-discrepancy sequences.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] These sequences "fill" the area better and sample the most important points more frequently, so quasi-Monte Carlo methods can often converge on the integral more quickly.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Another class of methods for sampling points in a volume is to simulate random walks over it (Markov chain Monte Carlo).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Such methods include the Metropolis–Hastings algorithm, Gibbs sampling, Wang and Landau algorithm, and interacting type MCMC methodologies such as the sequential Monte Carlo samplers.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Another powerful and very popular application for random numbers in numerical simulation is in numerical optimization.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The problem is to minimize (or maximize) functions of some vector that often has many dimensions.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Many problems can be phrased in this way: for example, a computer chess program could be seen as trying to find the set of, say, 10 moves that produces the best evaluation function at the end.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] In the traveling salesman problem the goal is to minimize distance traveled.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] There are also applications to engineering design, such as multidisciplinary design optimization.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] It has been applied with quasi-one-dimensional models to solve particle dynamics problems by efficiently exploring large configuration space.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Reference is a comprehensive review of many issues related to simulation and optimization.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The traveling salesman problem is what is called a conventional optimization problem.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] That is, all the facts (distances between each destination point) needed to determine the optimal path to follow are known with certainty and the goal is to run through the possible travel choices to come up with the one with the lowest total distance.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] If instead of the goal being to minimize the total distance traveled to visit each desired destination but rather to minimize the total time needed to reach each destination, this goes beyond conventional optimization since travel time is inherently uncertain (traffic jams, time of day, etc.).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Probabilistic formulation of inverse problems leads to the definition of a probability distribution in the model space.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] This probability distribution combines prior information with new information obtained by measuring some observable parameters (data).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] As, in the general case, the theory linking data with model parameters is nonlinear, the posterior probability in the model space may not be easy to describe (it may be multimodal, some moments may not be defined, etc.).
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] When analyzing an inverse problem, obtaining a maximum likelihood model is usually not sufficient, as normally information on the resolution power of the data is desired.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] In the general case many parameters are modeled, and an inspection of the marginal probability densities of interest may be impractical, or even useless.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] But it is possible to pseudorandomly generate a large collection of models according to the posterior probability distribution and to analyze and display the models in such a way that information on the relative likelihoods of model properties is conveyed to the spectator.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] This can be accomplished by means of an efficient Monte Carlo method, even in cases where no explicit formula for the *a priori* distribution is available.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The best-known importance sampling method, the Metropolis algorithm, can be generalized, and this gives a method that allows analysis of (possibly highly nonlinear) inverse problems with complex *a priori* information and data with an arbitrary noise distribution.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] Popular exposition of the Monte Carlo Method was conducted by McCracken.
[src:markov-chain-monte-carlo/monte-carlo-method] The method's general philosophy was discussed by Elishakoff and Grüne-Yanoff and Weirich.
